  title: Record of an Eastern Journey
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the autumn of the ninth year of Zhizheng, the year of jizhou, I set out to tour Mount Kumgang. On the fourteenth day, I departed from Songdo. On the twenty-first day, I crossed over Cheonma Ridge and lodged at the foot of the mountain in Jangyang County, some thirty li from the mountain. At dawn I took a simple meal and began climbing, but clouds and mist grew thick and dark. The locals told me that those who come to view Pungak Mountain often turn back without seeing anything due to such clouds and fog. All my companions looked worried, and we fell silent in prayer.

    When we drew within five li of the mountain, the dark clouds began to thin, and sunlight broke through. Ascending to Bae Peak, the sky cleared and the air grew pure. The mountain shone as if scraped clean by a blade. The famed twelve thousand peaks could be counted one by one. All who enter this mountain must pass through this peak. Once you ascend the peak, you see the mountain, and seeing the mountain, you cannot help but bow—thus it is called Bae Peak.

    In ancient times there were no buildings on the peak; stones were piled to make a platform for rest. In the year dinghao of Zhizheng, the now-Minister Jiang Kong, acting on the Emperor's command, came to cast a great bell and erected a bell tower upon this peak. Beside it he built a Buddhist hall to house the monks who ring it. The gold and jade gleam brilliantly, their light shooting across the snow-capped peaks—truly a magnificent sight at the mountain's entrance. Before noon we reached Pyohu Temple for a brief rest. A young novice offered to guide us up the mountain. He said that to the east lies the Bodhisattva Cave of Universal Virtue, which pilgrims must visit first, though the path is deep and treacherous. To the northwest stands Jeongyang Hermitage, founded by our Grand Progenitor and home to the statue of Bodhisattva Faqiji. Though steep, it is relatively accessible, and from its summit one can behold all the peaks of Pungak Mountain at once.

    I replied, "The Bodhisattva dwells everywhere. I have come to observe the sublime landscape of this mountain. Why not go there first?" With that, we climbed, and indeed my wish was fully satisfied. As evening approached and we could not stay on the mountain, I descended via Sinrim and the Three Buddhas hermitages, following a stream downward until we reached Jangan Temple as dusk fell.

    We left the mountain the next morning. From Cheolwon to the mountain is three hundred li; thus from the capital it is truly over five hundred li. Yet the intervening rivers and overlapping ridges create such deep and treacherous terrain that travel through this mountain is most arduous. I have heard that this mountain is renowned in Buddhist scriptures and known throughout the world; even people from distant lands such as India sometimes come to behold it. Generally, what one sees falls short of what one has heard. Our people who have visited Western Shu's Mount Emei and Southern Yue's Mount Putuo all say the reality does not match the reputation. Though I have not seen Emei or Putuo, what I beheld at this mountain truly exceeds all I had heard. Even the skill of master painters and the talents of poets cannot adequately describe its forms.

    On the twenty-third day, from Jangan Temple we crossed over the western ridge of Cheonma and reached Tonggou. All who enter the mountain via Cheonma's two ridges look back at the peaks from the passes, so those ascending into the mountain do not fear the steep terrain. But returning downward from the mountain, only then does one understand the true difficulty. The western ridge is somewhat lower, requiring three li of ascent and descent, extremely steep—it is called Hair-Breaking Ridge.

    On the twenty-fourth day we reached Huiyang Prefecture and stayed one day. On the twenty-sixth day we crossed over Cheolryeong Pass and lodged at Boklryeong County. Cheolryeong is a vital stronghold to the east of our nation. As the saying goes, "One man guarding the gate can hold back ten thousand." Thus the regions east of the ridge—Gangneung and other provinces—are called Gwandong. In the gengyin year of Zhiyuan, bandits from the rebel Wang Naiyan's faction, including Hadan, fled north and came east. They breached through open districts and invaded Gwandong. The court sent myriarchoi such as Na Yu to command troops and defend Cheolryeong Pass. Yet when the bandits plundered regions west of Hwa and Deung provinces and reached Deung, they sent scouts ahead. Learning of the bandits' approach, Na Yu abandoned the pass and fled. Thus the invaders overran our lands like conquerors of an empty realm. The entire nation was thrown into chaos; the people suffered greatly. Many fled to mountain fortresses or island hideaways to escape their swords. Only by seeking aid from the Yuan court could we finally destroy them. Now, seeing the formidable danger of Cheolryeong Pass myself, I understand that if one man truly defended it, even thousands of attackers could not breach it in years. How cowardly was Na Yu!

    On the twenty-seventh day we reached Deung and stayed two days. It is now called Hwa Province. On the thirtieth day we set out early from Hwa, embarked by boat at Hak Port, and entered the sea to view Kuk Island. The island lies some ten li from shore, entered from its southwestern corner. Along the waterline spreads white sand like a bolt of silk. Above it lies level ground of five or six mu, shaped like half a jade disc. In the center are ruins of buildings; locals say a monk once dwelled here. Above this rises a ridge of mountains like a jade ring, not very high, covered in wild vines, with no trees—merely a low earthen mound at first glance.

    Sailing westward, the cliffs and banks grew distinctive. The cliff stones are all squared and arranged in regular array, standing upright like walls. The shore stones are all round and arranged in rows, each face could seat one person, though not arranged with perfect order. After passing several hundred paces, the cliff rose perhaps several hundred feet, the stones white, squared, of uniform length. Upon each ridge's summit rests a small stone like the finial of a monument pillar. Gazing upward, my spirit trembled with awe. There was a small cavern; we poled the boat inward, but it narrowed until the boat could pass no further. The cavern seemed fathomless. The stones on either side were arranged as uniformly as the outer face, and below hung stone formations as flat and regular as an inverted chessboard—as if carved by one great tool. From this one understands that the entire island consists of such bundled rectangular stone columns. The cavern seemed so cavernous and dreadful that we dared not linger and turned the boat northward.

    We found another face arranged like a folding screen. Abandoning the boat, we wandered and explored. The stones and caverns resembled those outside, but the cliffs were not so high and the ground below somewhat easier. Rounded stones arranged in rows could accommodate a thousand people—here those who tour must rest. Some linger and drink; fearing the wind might rise and that this is no dwelling place, we moved eastward along the cliff. After several hundred more paces, the cliff stones grew strange, forming a pattern like a metal net, holding water and wearing smooth small rounded stones, five or six zhang long, each line identical, covering every face. Locals call these the "iron-net stones." This represents the general aspect of Kuk Island; the truly strange and extraordinary forms defy description by brush or tongue. Truly one cannot fathom how the Creator brought this to such perfection.

    Returning to the port, we raised wine and toasted one another—partly to having witnessed such a sublime scene, partly that wind and waves had not arisen. From the port we poled up into the waters called Hak Port and ascended the Commander's Platform. A hundred li of crystalline lake, one solitary islet—another wondrous sight indeed. Evening came and we could not linger, so we lodged at the county inn.

    On the first day of the ninth month we crossed over the eastern ridge of Heup Valley. We inquired about entering Pierced Island, hearing it has a passage running north and south through which wind and tide flow freely. Beyond Pierced Island, crossing the sea southward, one can reach Four Immortals Pavilion, a distance of eight or nine li; and beyond that, crossing further south another ten-odd li reaches Gold Orchid Cavern. The scenes visible from a boat are indescribable. This day a gentle wind arose making travel by boat impossible, so we did not enter the cavern. Instead we sailed along the coast to Four Immortals Pavilion, where the prefect of Ae Prefecture, Sir Shen, awaited us on the pavilion. The so-called Four Immortal Peaks have stones standing bundled together in rectangular columns much like Kuk Island, save their color is russet and the cliff stones are more irregular. Looking down from above, the four peaks stand distinct and steep, the broken cliffs treacherous, overlooking the eastern sea for ten thousand li while facing western ridges a thousand fold. Truly this is the grand vista of Gwandong. An old stone monument once stood on the cliff, but now only its traces remain. At the eastern peak stood an ancient stele, its surface worn smooth with time, not a single character legible—I know not from what era it was raised.

    People say that in the Silla era, there were four Immortal Youths named Yeongrang and Surangrang who wandered the sea with three thousand disciples; perhaps they erected this monument. But this cannot be verified. Before the Four Immortal Peaks stood a small pavilion where we set out wine. Evening fell before we departed, reaching Tongju to lodge.

    Tongju stands at the northern corner of the old fortress of Geumran County. There is a stone cavern; locals call it Gold Orchid Cavern, the dwelling place of the Bodhisattva Avalokitesvara. The next day we boarded a boat and sailed inland, observing from a distance what seemed faintly like the Bodhisattva's form within the cavern. Because the cavern is deep and narrow, we could not enter. The boatman said, "I have lived here long. From Yuan dynasty envoys and ministers of our realm, down to humble sightseers of all ranks, none fail to wish to visit. Each time I guide them by boat. In truth I grew weary of it. Once I fashioned a small hollowed log and ventured alone into the cavern, reaching its end. I saw nothing extraordinary. Feeling the stone with my hands, it was merely moss-covered rock. Yet when I emerged and turned to look back, something resembling a form appeared. Alas, was my sincerity insufficient? Or was it my constant thoughts creating illusion—what is called thought-taking-form?"

    Hearing this, I understood considerably. East of the cavern lies a stone pool—locals say it is where the Bodhisattva bathes. Nearby cluster strange rocks, each perhaps the size of a fist, covering several mu in area, all tilted awry. Locals call these the "Aching-Feet Rocks," saying the Bodhisattva's feet once pressed upon them in pain, causing them to tilt thus. From Gold Orchid we went to Imdo County to lodge.

    On the third day we reached Goseong Prefecture. From Tongju to Goseong is one hundred fifty li, truly the far side of Mount Pungak. Its mountains are like cliff-cuts, most treacherous; locals call it the Outer Mountain—it rivals the Inner Mountain in its strange wonders. To its southeast stands Yudaeom Temple, which houses a great bell and bronze statues of fifty-three Buddhas. Locals say that in Silla times, these fifty-three Buddhas rode this bell across the sea from Western India, landing on Goseong's coast before coming to rest at Yudaeom.

    South of Goseong lies Fehang Village, truly at the mountain's base. From Fehang one climbs steeply for sixty li to reach Yudaeom. I had originally agreed with my companions that we must reach Yudaeom to see the famous bell and Buddha statues. But the journey was long, the way steep, our horses' backs were sore and their hooves painful, and some lagged behind. Thus we could not climb further.

    On the fourth day we rose early and reached Three-Day Port, located some five li north of the city. We boarded a boat to a small island in the southwest, where a single enormous stone rises like a dome. Upon its summit is a stone chamber within which sits a stone Buddha—the common name is the Maitreya Hall. Upon the cliff's northeastern face appear six characters in red ink. Drawing near, we saw two lines of three characters each reading: "Surangrang's disciples—Namseok the younger," with Surangrang's name clearly visible but the two characters below barely discernible. In ancient times locals, tired of maintaining accommodations for visitors, scraped at them; though the knife went five cun deep, the carved strokes did not vanish. This is why those two characters remain unclear.

    We then reboarded and ascended to Four Immortals Pavilion, also an island in the lake. Leaning on the railing and looking about, what are called the Thirty-Six Peaks have their reflections inverted on the lake's surface. The lake spans perhaps a hundred li, so clear and deep it shimmers endlessly—truly the finest landscape of Gwandong, second only to Kuk Island. At that moment no prefect was in office, so the local magistrates arranged a modest gathering. Being unable to drink alone, I ordered the boats away. People say this lake is where the Four Immortals played, and its thirty-six peaks once bore monuments which the official Hu Zongdan collected and sank into the water. Still the stone bases remain. This Hu Zongdan was from Tang, in Li Sheng's time, who came to serve our realm. Touring five provinces, wherever he went he would seize monuments and stelae, scraping away their inscriptions, smashing them, or sinking them. Even famous bells and stone chimes he would melt metal to silence. Examples appear in the monuments at Cold Pine, Massed Stones, and Three-Day Port, and in the bell of Fengde Temple at Gyerim Prefecture.

    Four Immortals Pavilion was established when Park Sookjung served as Resident Commandant, with Master Igjae composing the inscription. From Three-Day Port we crossed the southern river of the city, passed Anchang County pavilion, and lodged at Myeongpa Station.

    On the fifth day we lodged in Goseong and stayed another day. On the seventh day the host arranged a gathering at Seonyou Pond where we drank briefly, passed Cheonggan Station, ascended Mangyeong Platform for more wine, and lodged at Ingrals Village.

    On the eighth day we sailed on Yeongrang Lake. Evening fell before we could reach its source, so we arrived at Naksan Temple where we paid respects to the Bodhisattva in White. Locals say this is the Bodhisattva's dwelling place; at the mountain's base is a cavern said to be her entry point. Late in the day we reached Yangju and lodged.

    The next day was the Ninth Day festival, yet rain fell. We raised chrysanthemum wine on the upper story. On the tenth day we lodged at Dongsan County, which has the Observation Pavilion. On the eleventh day we lodged at Yeon Valley County.

    On the twelfth day, the Resident Commandant of Gangneung, Sungsan Sir Lee, awaited us at Mirror Port. We boarded two boats and sang and danced mid-channel. Before sunset we ascended Mirror Port Platform. The platform had no structure previously; recently an enthusiast built this pavilion. Upon it stands an old Immortal's stone kitchen for brewing tea. Matched with Three-Day Port, the view is comparable, though more brilliant and remote. Rain fell and we stayed an extra day. Departing the river city, we toured the Manjusri Hall where locals say statues of Manjusri and Samantabhadra rose from the earth. To the east stood the Four Immortals Monument until Hu Zongdan sank it—only the turtle base remains. We drank a farewell wine at Cold Pine Pavilion, a place where the Four Immortals also roamed. The locals, tired of constant visitors, demolished the structure; the pines were burned by wildfire, leaving only the stone kitchen, stone pool, and two stone wells nearby—these too were the Immortals' tea implements.

    South of the pavilion lies Anin Station. Evening had come, we could not cross the ridge, so we lodged there. The next day we departed, passing the station. Eastern Peak was most treacherous. We reached Deungmyeong Temple and viewed the Sunrise Platform, then sailed along the coast eastward, rested at River Village, crossed a ridge, and lodged at Yugye County.

    On the twelfth day we lodged at Samcheok County. The next day we ascended the western tower and freely surveyed the so-called Fifty Rivers and Eight Vistas, then departed to Gyeokgo Station. The station lies thirty li from the county seat; at the fifteen li mark upon a sea-facing cliff stands another Commander's Platform—another extraordinary scene. We drank there and lodged at the station house.

    On the eighteenth day we lodged at Ugyeon Station. On the nineteenth day we reached Ulgjin and stayed one day. On the twenty-first day we departed early. Ten li south of Ulgjin County lies Seongryou Temple, situated beneath a cliff beside a long stream. The cliff stones rise a thousand feet sheer. Within the cliff is a small aperture called Seongryou Cavern, fathomless and lightless—impossible to enter without torches. We had a temple monk carry a torch to guide us, preceded and followed by local folk accustomed to entering. The cavern mouth was narrow; after crawling four or five paces it widened enough to rise. A few more steps revealed a chasm of perhaps three zhang; we descended by ladder. Gradually the ground leveled and opened. After dozens of paces lay level ground spanning several mu. The stones on either side displayed wondrous forms. Another ten paces brought a narrower cavern mouth; we proceeded by crawling. Below lay muddy water; mats were spread to prevent soaking. After seven or eight paces it opened wider; the stones grew ever stranger, some like banners, some like stupas.

    Another dozen paces and the stones grew most fantastic, their forms innumerable and unnameable. The banner and stupa forms grew longer, broader, higher, more vast. A few more paces revealed Buddha-like and high-monk-like forms, and then a pool of exceeding clarity spanning several mu. Within stood two stones—one resembling a wheel hub, one a vase. Above and beside them hung five-colored banners and canopies brilliant and splendid. Initially I thought these stone formations would be soft, not hardened, so I tapped one with my walking stick. Each produced a sound; their lengths created clear and murky tones like a stone chime. Locals said that continuing along the pool revealed even greater wonders, but I deemed this not a place for common frivolity and urged departing. Many holes line the sides; those entering by mistake cannot exit. When I asked about the cavern's depth, they replied no one has ever reached its end, though some claim it connects to Pyeongae coast, distant twenty-odd li.

    At first I borrowed a servant's clothes and headdress to prevent soiling, but upon exiting changed garments and washed thoroughly. It was like wandering in the Realm of Transformation and suddenly awakening. Long I have pondered: the Creator's mysteries cannot mostly be fathomed. At Kuk Island and especially here do I perceive this most clearly. Did these arise naturally? Or were they deliberately made? If natural, how could such craftsmanship be perfected to this degree? If deliberately made, though even demonic artistry and divine power labored countless ages, how could such an extreme be reached?

    This day we reached Pyeongae County. Five li before the county, ten thousand pines stand, and among them a pavilion named Crossing-Pine Pavilion. The Four Immortals once passed here by chance, hence the name. Pyeongae County marks the southern boundary of Gangneung Province. From Cheolryeong in the north to Pyeongae in the south spans perhaps twelve hundred li. South of Pyeongae lies the border of Gyeongsang Province, which I have previously traveled. Thus I do not record it here.
  footnotes:
    - Zhizheng 9 (至正九年) corresponds to 1349 CE during the Yuan Dynasty.
    - Mount Kumgang (金剛山), also known as Pungak Mountain (楓岳山), is a sacred site in Korean Buddhism and landscape tradition, famous for its twelve thousand peaks.
    - The Four Immortal Youths (四仙童) are legendary figures in Korean Buddhist mythology said to have roamed the eastern coastal regions.
    - Hu Zongdan (胡宗旦) was an official from Tang who served in Korea and systematically removed or defaced historical monuments during his tenure, an act viewed negatively by the author.
    - This travelogue records one of the most important pre-modern Korean landscape journeys, blending Buddhist pilgrimage, natural observation, and historical reflection.
